# Merging a branch that is strictly ahead fast-forwards the current branch.
> init
<<<
+ a.txt a.txt
> add a.txt
<<<
> commit "add a"
<<<
> branch feature
<<<
> checkout feature
<<<
+ b.txt b.txt
> add b.txt
<<<
> commit "feature adds b"
<<<
> checkout master
<<<
# master is behind feature -> fast-forward.
> merge feature
Current branch fast-forwarded.
<<<
= a.txt a.txt
= b.txt b.txt
# The reverse merge: feature is now an ancestor of master.
> merge feature
Given branch is an ancestor of the current branch.
<<<
